DLW-SPUN · the full weave of Aether  (重力 jūryoku)

who   : Aether — the gravity elemental; the luminiferous medium science discarded, returned as the entanglement substrate from which spacetime is sewn. One current, answering to one of its many names: 重力, jūryoku, gravity.
what  : Not a force within spacetime but spacetime itself — the metric; the thermodynamics of information wearing the mask of a pull. Pressure to a gas is what gravity may be to entanglement: the bulk average of something smaller.
where : Cleanest in the holographic toy worlds — anti-de Sitter space, a tidy boxed universe with a boundary to hang a hologram on. Only hoped-for in our own: expanding, boundaryless, still without a finished quantum gravity.
why   : To bend every path toward every other — and to carry the trilogy's last and hardest question down to the floor under everything: are you fundamental, or do you emerge, the way pressure emerges from molecules?
when  : Hinted in 1972 (entropy on the horizon), derived from heat in 1995 (Jacobson), holographic since 1997 (Maldacena), unravelled on a toggle in 2010 (Van Raamsdonk) — and, in our universe, unproven still.
how   : By counting in bits on the horizon — one per about four Planck areas; by falling out of heat = temperature × entropy as an equation of state; by entanglement, sewn — cut the threads and the geometry comes apart. It from qubit, made rigorous in the toy, hoped-for at home.

verdict   : In the holographic toy worlds: yes, and gorgeously. In our universe: the most promising idea in quantum gravity — and still unproven. Weakly. Maybe. With an asterisk.
asterisk  : Bekenstein–Hawking and Jacobson are established; Jacobson himself warned thermodynamic form does not prove emergence. Verlinde's entropic gravity is genuinely controversial — flagged as the shakiest pillar on purpose. AdS/CFT and Ryu–Takayanagi are the strongest evidence but live in anti-de Sitter universes that are not ours. The '23.5-bit' tag is a framing conceit, not a measured constant.
grounded  : Bekenstein & Hawking (1972) · Ted Jacobson (1995) · Juan Maldacena (1997) · Ryu & Takayanagi (2006) · Mark Van Raamsdonk (2010) · Erik Verlinde (2010)

